05401nam a22007095i 9780824860806DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20102010hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248608067 a10.1515/97808248608062doi  a(DE-B1597)484538  a(OCoLC)794925345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aMUS0280002bisacsh04a782.1095192221 aKillick, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Search of Korean Traditional Opera :bDiscourses of Changguk /cAndrew Killick. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b43 b&w illustrations, 8 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the International Center for Korean Studies, Korea University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList Of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. A Night At The Korean Opera -- tChapter Two. Origins And Origin Myths -- tChapter Three. Ch’Anggŭk In Colonial Korea -- tChapter Four. Women’s National Drama: Yŏsŏng Kukkŭk -- tChapter Five. Inventing A Tradition? The National Changgeuk Company Of Korea -- tChapter Six. Stories And Themes: What Is Ch’Anggŭk About? -- tChapter Seven. Constructing The Nation Through Sound: The Music Of Ch’Anggŭk -- tChapter Eight. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first book on Korean opera in a language other than Korean. Its subject is ch’angguk, a form of musical theater that has developed over the last hundred years from the older narrative singing tradition of p’ansori. Andrew Killick examines the history and current practice of ch’angguk as an ongoing attempt to invent a traditional Korean opera form to compare with those of neighboring China and Japan. In this, the work addresses a growing interest within the fields of ethnomusicology and Asian studies in the adaptation of traditional arts to conditions in the modern world. Ch’angguk presents an intriguing case in that, unlike the "invented traditions" described in Hobsbawm and Ranger's influential book that were firmly established within a few years of their invention, ch’angguk remains in a marginal position relative to recognized traditional art forms such as South Korea’s "Important Intangible Cultural Properties" after more than a century. Performers, writers, directors, and historians have looked for ways to make the genre more traditional, including looking outside Korea for comparisons with traditional theater forms in other countries and for recognition of ch’angguk as a national art form by international audiences.For the benefit of readers who have not seen ch’angguk performed, the author begins with a detailed description of a typical performance, illustrated with photographs and musical examples, followed by a history of the genre—from its still disputed origins in the early twentieth century through a major revival under Japanese colonial rule and the flourishing of an all-female version (yosong kukkuk) after Liberation to the efforts of the National Changgeuk Company and others to establish ch’angguk as Korean traditional opera. Killick concludes with analyses of the stories and music of ch’angguk and a personal view on developing a Korean national theater form for international audiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2